Blockchain Engineer
text:
I'm looking for someone to finish a software project that's partially built. The original engineer will help guide the remaining parts of the project.

This is a private blockchain that will augment/disintermediate a discrete and significant existing payment rail. It is a fintech, the second I've started. The first was also a fintech that augmented/disintermediated a key aspect of swaps and derivatives.

Applicants will need to sign a non-disclosure agreement. Payment will be in cash and/or equity.

This is a "project" and can be done remotely. However, ideally the right individual will be interested in being one of the early employees and that will require being in the Boston area.

Knowledge of the banking system is helpful but not necessary. Additionally, experience is not as important as technical brilliance. Blockchain experience is a requirement.

Please send a CV to ben@mustanggroup.com

Ask HN: Non-IT Job is slowly killing me, becoming a dev is a year?
text:
TLDR: CEO smokes cigarettes at my non-related IT job (first one ever) with no WFH option, want to become a dev if possible remote by studying/developing my skills on the evenings within a year

I recently finished my 2 year education in an unrelated field to IT (Logistics), and was very lucky to find my first job at what seemed to be a pretty nice company straight out of vocational school.

Well, as it turns out, the CEO of the company smokes cigarettes in his office, and I can smell all of the smoke from where I work at. I tried talking to my manager about this, he told me he can do nothing about this, considering the CEO is the owner of a multi-million dollar company. BTW, I am from Western Europe, totally illegal. If I rat them out to the authorities, even anonymously, I am sure they'd take vengeance on me.

I'm at a complete loss right now, second hand smoking is as everyone knows deadly, and it's taken me a LOT of work (networking, studying, etc...) to get this (first ever) job. I'm in my early 20s.

I will start wearing a FFP3/N100 mask from now on to work (even if they're not fully effective) and do everything I can to avoid the smoke/odor.

Quitting is almost a non-starter because I'd be unhireable in a field where there's work but there's not that much work. Plus, who would hire someone who quit his job 3 months into it?

I actually went to college for CS for a year, but ended up dropping out after failing all of my subjects due to what I believe lack of a work ethic (I mean, I literally even failed a non-CS related subject). I'm also not that bright, I am not going to lie.

So, to avoid all of this... or at least give it a try at avoiding all of this, I would like to become a remote (or not!) dev within a year, by doing everything I can (projects, learning how to code, networking, etc.) in my evenings.

I know this is going to be hell of earth for me, but I have no alternative -there is no guarantee another job within the logistics industry doesn't have something similar to this.

Please, tell me, what should I try learning to accomplish this, I don't care, web, programming, databases, etc... It is a matter of life and/or death (eventually) for me.

Thank you.

Ask HN: How to find a remote entry job? (EU)
text:
Hello HN.

I hope one of you people can help me. I've never had a proper "job". My life has been filled with setbacks and I'm currently in my 20s.

After many wasted years I finally completed an apprenticeship in computer science which is titled "Computer Science Expert" (although I'm far from being an expert). I've moved countries and since been hopelessly looking for work.

I got all basic/surface level skills about programming (primarily python and some c++ and little java), I understand html/css, networking, servers and batch/powershell/bash scripting.

I'm willing to learn new things and can expand my knowledge rather quickly. What I'm ultimately looking for is a 100% remote job (I'm in the EU and an EU citizen) that gives me the opportunity to get started and grow from there. Ideally something that allows me to have flexible work hours as I want to help my wife with the baby whenever it's needed.

To everybody who too the time to read through all of this: thank you and I wish you a nice day :)

Ask HN: From Spreadsheets to Data Warehouse
text:
I am a spreadsheets guru/nerd.

At work I have build a spreadsheet based system where we download csv files from a few systems and with a series of spreadsheet, we enrich the data, and compile business reports.

But the entire system is now taxed by the size of the data files and the complexity of the reports that keep piling up.

I want to migrate to a small Data Warehouse; but I need to educate myself.

From the research that I have done I need to learn SQL and Python. I am willing to put on the time.

So, these are my 2 questions for HN:

1. What's the best and inexpensive way to learn SQL and Python online. Low cost is fine since the company will pay for it, but the budget is limited.

2. Is there an online class that is hands-on, so that I can actually build my data warehouse as I am studying?

Thanks in Advance.

Ask HN: A place to collect reverse-engineered WiFi config protocols?
text:
Many connected devices support some sort of open or otherwise cross-platform protocol for the service they provide, but quite a lot of them hide setup and WiFi config behind some shoddy proprietary app. Cough, printers, cough.

So even if devices could be used with something else than the "supported" OS, or beyond the lifetime of said shoddy app, they cannot be set up without it.

While these companies definitely deserve to be on a wall of shame, surely some protocols also get reverse-engineered by creative users that just want things to work. Is there some place to collect and share such information in the open?
